<div class="container">
  <div style="display: flex">
    <h1 style="white-space: nowrap">ABAI QUNANBAIULY</h1>
    <div>
      <p class="header-text" style="padding-left: 166px; padding-top: 5px">
        word of admonition
      </p>
      <p class="header-text" style="padding-left: 207px; padding-top: 5px">
        biography
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <h3 style="padding-left: 636px">10.08.1845 – 06.07.1904</h3>
  <div class="divider"></div>

  <div class="text-container">
    <div class="text-left">
      <a href="/abay_app/en">
        <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/Group 4.svg" alt="" style="margin: 0; padding-bottom: 250px"/>
      </a>
      <h6 style="padding-bottom: 5px">born</h6>
      <h6 style="padding-bottom: 20px">10.08.1845</h6>
      <h6>Semipalatinsk</h6>
    </div>
    <div class="text-right">
      <div
              class="description"
              style="padding-left: 149px; padding-top: 30px"
      >
        Abai was born in the present-day Abay District of East Kazakhstan,
        originally part of the Russian Empire. His Muslim parents, Qunanbai
        and Uljan, initially named him Ibrahim. As a child, he studied under
        Mullah Ahmed Ryza At a local
      </div>
      <div class="description" style="padding-left: 491px">
        madrasah, where he received the nickname “Abai,” meaning “careful.”
        His father's wealth allowed him to attend a Russian secondary school
        in Semipalatinsk.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div style="padding-top: 90px; padding-left: 285px">
    <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/A-ylbaj_Abaj-T-ra-ul-1896-zh_-transformed 1.png" alt="" />
    <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/A-ylbaj_Abaj-T-ra-ul-1896-zh_-transformed 2.png"
            style="padding-left: 20px"
            alt=""
    />
  </div>
  <div class="description" style="padding-left: 636px; padding-top: 30px">
    At the same time, he attended a
  </div>
  <div class="description" style="padding-left: 296px">
    Russian school. By the end of his studies he began to write poems, at
    first attributing their authorship to his friend Kokpai Dzhantasov. From
    the age of 13, his father Kunanbai began to train Abay to be the head of
    the family.
  </div>
  <div style="padding-left: 636px; padding-top: 30px">
    <p>
      At the age of 28, Abay walked away from it, completely engaged in
      self-education, but only by the age of 40 he created his first adult
      poems.
    </p>
    <p style="padding-top: 10px">
      A significant event for Abay was his association with the political
      exiles Eugene Michaelis, Nifont Dolgopolov, and Severin Gross
    </p>
  </div>
  <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/A-ylbaj_Abaj-T-ra-ul-1896-zh_-transformed 3.png"
          alt=""
          style="padding-left: 296px; padding-top: 30px"
  />
  <div class="flex-container" style="padding-top: 90px">
    <h3>worldview</h3>
    <div class="short-divider"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="description" style="padding-left: 645px">
    Abai Kunanbayev was shaped by
  </div>
  <div class="description" style="padding-left: 296px">
    both Eastern and Western cultures. Familiar from a young age with works
    of philosophers like Ferdowsi, Navoi, Nizami, and Ibn Sina, his interest
    in European culture was later stimulated by his Russian education and
    interactions with Russian political exiles.
  </div>
  <div style="display: flex; padding-top: 30px">
    <div style="display: flex; margin: 0">
      <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/ABAI1 1.png" alt="" style="padding-left: 296px" />
      <p style="padding-left: 20px; width: 250px">
        Abai introduced Kazakhs to European culture through his translations
        of Pushkin, Lermontov, Krylov, Goethe, and Byron.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>
        Abai supported democratic changes, advocated for laws that
        benefitted the people, and condemned societal ills like corruption
        and abuse of power.
      </p>
      <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/oKDbbVY4dUQ 1.png" alt="" style="padding-top: 119px" />
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="flex-container" style="padding-top: 90px">
    <h3 style="width: 237px">Creativity</h3>
    <div class="short-divider"></div>
  </div>
  <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/60ac44470a20d97a02adcce63fe8d9b4-transformed 1.png"
          alt=""
          style="padding-left: 296px"
  />
  <div class="description" style="padding-left: 636px; padding-top: 22px">
    He is widely known for his prose
  </div>
  <div class="description" style="padding-left: 296px">
    poem <strong>Words of Exhortation</strong> - "Kara soz" ("A simple
    word"), translated into many languages. It consists of 45 short parables
    on the themes of morals, law and history.
  </div>
  <div style="display: flex; padding-left: 296px; padding-top: 30px">
    <img src="${pageContext.request.contextPath}/view/images/iH5EeNrh_gE 1.png" alt="" />
    <div style="padding-left: 232px">
      <p>
        Abay left about 170 poems, poems, prose, musical works. He is an
        acknowledged innovator in Kazakh poetry;
      </p>
      <p style="padding-top: 10px">
        He introduced new rhymes and verse sizes (six- and eight-poems).
        This manifested itself in numerous poems dedicated to the seasons.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="divider" style="margin-top: 180px"></div>
  <div style="display: flex; margin-top: 20px">
    <div>
      <div class="footer-quote">
        “The worst kind of man is a man with no aspirations.“
      </div>
      <div class="footer-quote">— Abai Qunanbaiuly</div>
    </div>
